<TEXT>
MANY of Sweden's bank customers are worried that the unprecedented increase
in the marginal rate - the rate at which the central bank lends to other
banks - would be reflected in higher interest rates on home loans and
mortgages, Our Foreign Staff writes.
Svenska Handelsbanken, one of the biggest commercial banks in Sweden, told
customers yesterday that if they wanted to take out new loans, the bank
would not be able to provide any indication yet of where the interest rates
would be pitched.
Some mortgage lenders have already acted on the news and raised mortgage
rates. Statshypotek, a mortgage lender, raised its rate from 17.5 per cent
on Tuesday to 24 per cent yesterday. Sweden's main savings bank raised rates
on personal loans by 2.5 percentage points to 18-20 per cent.
