<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / Major stresses solid opposition to devaluation: Pound's
realignment would be 'betrayal'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night staked his government's political authority on the
value of sterling with an uncompromising refusal to contemplate devaluation
in the European exchange rate mechanism.
In a speech billed by Downing Street as unequivocal evidence of his
determination to resist the speculation on currency markets, the prime
minister said a realignment of the pound's ERM parity would be 'a betrayal
of our future'.
Senior aides said the comments were intended to signal that even if other
European currencies were devalued against the D-mark in a general ERM
realignment, the government would seek to hold sterling's central rate at
DM2.95.
But the speech coincided with a new survey from the Confederation of British
Industry which suggested there was little chance of a recovery in consumer
confidence before the end of the year.
More than two-thirds of retailers, who continue to suffer from consumers'
fear of losing their jobs and high levels of household debt, said they did
not expect the business situation to improve over the next three months.
Wholesalers and car traders expected conditions to worsen.
As the pound continued to hover just above its DM2.7780 floor on the foreign
exchange markets, the survey pointed to a reversal during the summer of a
modest improvement in the annual growth rate of retail sales earlier in the
year.
Sterling closed in London unchanged on the day at DM2.7875. In New York it
rose to DM2.7917, although it shed nearly 2 cents against the dollar which
was strengthened by Mr Major's remarks that the ERM's problems were being
exaggerated by the weak US currency.
The government came under further attack yesterday from senior
industrialists who urged action to help economic recovery.
Mr Major's remarks came as Sir Michael Angus, CBI president, voiced concern
at the same meeting about the depths of the recession. He said that, while
business supported the government's stance over the ERM, he believed other
measures could be taken to stimulate recovery.
Elsewhere Mr Martin Laing, chairman of the building group John Laing,
criticised the government's failure to stimulate the economy while
unemployment figures were mounting and construction companies were going
into receivership. Sir Owen Green, chairman of BTR, described market
conditions as an 'economic desert'.
Mr Major, who used the first cabinet meeting since the summer break to
congratulate Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, on his handling of the
currency turmoil, detailed the arguments against any devaluation.
Mr Lamont delivered a report to cabinet on the Treasury's strategy in
countering speculation against the pound. Although there was no discussion
of the strategy, senior ministers said the consensus around the cabinet
table was that the government has long been too deeply committed to the
present value of the pound to allow room for doubts.
One senior minister commented after the meeting that: 'Even those who would
have preferred not to have started from here (the present ERM parity)
believe there is no going back'.
The prime minister, speaking to the Scottish CBI in Glasgow, insisted that
the ERM had delivered the low inflation and the relative exchange rate
stability demanded by the business community. Maintaining sterling's parity
was essential to ensure that Britain preserved and improved on those gains.
Dismissing the inevitable 'chorus of quack doctors' calling for a reversal
of policy, Mr Major said: 'As the chancellor has made crystal clear, there
is going to be no devaluation, no realignment.' He continued: 'The soft
option,the devaluer's option, the inflationary option would be a betrayal of
our future; and it is not the government's policy'.
Mr Major, who repeated that defeat of inflation was a precondition of
sustained economic success, dismissed the arguments of those blaming the ERM
for the depth of the recession.
The painful 'problem of adjustment' after the build up of business and
individual debt was apparent throughout the industrialised world.
Alluding to the failure of past devaluations to deliver a sustained
improvement in Britain's competitiveness, he added: 'We must bite the
anti-inflation bullet or accept that we will be forever second-rate in
Europe.'
Ministers were predicting that the publication today of inflation figures
for August would further demonstrate that price rises were being brought
under control.
UK ECONOMY Page 8
Public expenditure body shapes up for battle
Page 9
Retailers report dismal sales levels
</TEXT>
