<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / Car dealer guilty in GM fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN McNamara, a car dealer on New York's Long Island, has pleaded guilty
to charges that he defrauded General Motors in a Dollars 6bn loan racket,
and that he used some of the money to bribe local officials so as to win
approval for real estate schemes.
The fraud has embarrassed GM's finance arm, General Motors Acceptance
Corporation, which has a reputation for strict credit controls. It has led
GM to shake up the subsidiary's management, and the group was forced to
write off Dollars 171m in loans.
Mr McNamara, aged 53, borrowed billions of dollars from General Motors over
more than a decade to finance the purchase of cars which did not exist. He
used new borrowings to pay off old debts, while siphoning off part of the
money for his own Dollars 400m business empire. He faces up to 20 years jail
and Dollars 800m in fines.
</TEXT>
