<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / International Company News: Third quarter rise at Paramount
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PARAMOUNT Communications, the publishing and entertainment group which last
month agreed to buy a string of US theme parks for Dollars 400m, yesterday
unveiled a 12 per cent rise in net profits for its third quarter, ended July
31.
Net income was Dollars 113.3m, or 95 cents a share, compared with Dollars
101.2m, or 86 cents a share in the same period of 1991. Revenues for the
three months were Dollars 1.06bn, against Dollars 963.9m.
Publishing operations, led by traditional second-half strength in
educational areas and gains in consumer publishing, reported Dollars 112.5m
of operating income, up only marginally year-on-year.
Entertainment operations, including the Hollywood studio, had Dollars 60.8m
of operating income, compared to Dollars 55.3m in the same period last year.
Paramount also earned Dollars 10.7m of net interest and other income in the
quarter.
Results from theatre operations declined because of lower contributions from
Paramount's Famous Players and partly-owned Cinamerica chains.
Madison Square Garden posted a smaller operating loss, thanks largely to the
leasing of the arena for the Democratic National Convention in July.
For the first nine months of Paramount's fiscal 1992, net profit totalled
Dollars 160m, a solid recovery from Dollars 38.9m in the first nine months
of fiscal 1991. Revenues for the period were Dollars 3.06bn, against Dollars
2.72bn.
On Wall Street, Paramount's share price closed yesterday at Dollars 45, up
by Dollars 1 1/8.
</TEXT>
