<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / International Company News: Setback to Black's bid for the
NY Daily News
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR CONRAD BLACK, the Canadian entrepreneur who owns London's Daily
Telegraph, last night suffered a major setback in his quest to acquire The
Daily News, the loss-making New York tabloid that used to be owned by the
late Mr Robert Maxwell.
A key aide to Mr Black said that after meeting the two largest and most
powerful of the newspaper's unions it had been decided to 'adjourn
temporarily our negotiations for The News'.
Mr Martin Maleska, the New York investment banker representing Mr Black in
the Daily News talks, said the decision came after leaders of the pressmen
and drivers unions made clear they favoured a rival offer from Mr Mortimer
Zuckerman, the owner of US News and World Report, the weekly news magazine.
The two unions represent 600 of the 2,000 employees at the Daily News.
Their co-operation is needed if a deal is to be consummated.
'We met with the pressmen and drivers unions and we decided we could not,
realistically, match Mr Zuckerman's proposals. So we have ceased our
negotiations with the drivers and pressmen this afternoon,' Mr Maleska said.
Mr Maleska added: 'We have been the lead horse in this race and we are now
realising that Mr Zuckerman has a commanding position vis-a-vis the major
unions, a position we cannot match.'
Mr Black had previously obtained a letter of intent from the management of
The Daily News, which last year filed for protection from creditors under US
bankruptcy law.
Any takeover still needs the approval of the unions and the creditors, as
well as Judge Tina Brozman of New York's bankruptcy court.
</TEXT>
