<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Curbs on regulators urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TUC made its first serious contribution to the national debate on the
regulation of utilities yesterday by calling for greater accountability for
the regulators and less favouritism for business customers.
Moving a motion on the regulation of public-service industries, Mr Tony
Young, general secretary of the NCU communications union, said: 'For too
long we have ignored the role that regulators have to play. We've seen them
as agents of the Tory government, instead of realising they could just as
easily work for the country.'
The call is a response to the government's sale of about 25 per cent of
British Telecom shares last year, which ruled out the prospect of a return
to state control of the company under any future Labour government.
Previously, the possibility of renationalisation prevented the NCU from
entering the regulation debate.
The motion urges new responsibilities for regulators to protect the needs of
all regions, promote training and research, and ensure that business and
individual customers benefit from new technology.
Mr Young criticised bodies such as Oftel, the telecommunications regulator,
for ignoring the public interest.
