</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH aerospace industry leaders yesterday called for closer European
collaboration in military aircraft production to fend off efforts by US
manufacturers to penetrate the European market.
Mr Serge Dassault, head of the Dassault military aircraft group, said he
favoured the development of several different and competing military
aircraft programmes in Europe but insisted that there should be greater
resolve on the part of European governments to keep the US out of the
market.
'European countries should form a bloc and stop buying US equipment,' he
added.
Mr Henri Martre, former chairman of Aerospatiale and the president of the
French Industry Aerospace Association, also urged for greater European
collaboration in the military field. He argued this was essential as long as
the US bought no European military aircraft.
Dassault is developing the Rafale, an advanced combat aircraft which
competes with the European Fighter Aircraft.
