<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / International Company News: GM enters US credit card market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL MOTORS yesterday became the latest big industrial company to enter
the US credit card market, with a competitively priced product christened
the GM Card.
The card, which GM says will offer rebates of up to Dollars 3,500 on the
purchase of a GM car or truck, marks an unusual departure for the largest US
motor vehicles group.
Together with other new cards on offer from industrial companies, the GM
plan could signal a competitive challenge for traditional bank issuers of
credit cards.
The GM card, issued in association with the Mastercard network, comes just a
week after General Electric, the US conglomerate, unveiled plans to launch
the GE Rewards MasterCard. Another company busy competing with bank issuers
is American Telephone &amp; Telegraph (AT&amp;T), which offers the Universal Card.
The GE card was criticised by some analysts last week because it carries a
high interest rate of 18.4 per cent and an annual Dollars 25 fee. By
contrast, GM offers a 16.4 per cent adjustable interest rate - current prime
plus 10.4 per cent - and no fee. The average rate being charged to US credit
card customers is 18 per cent.
The GM card was described yesterday by Mr Michael Losh, GM vice-president in
charge of North American vehicle sales and marketing, as 'a powerful and
innovative marketing tool that can help GM and its products stand above the
competition'. Mr Losh said GM would soon launch one of the biggest direct
mail and advertising campaigns in its history, with more than 30m Americans
receiving pre-approved GM card applications by post.
Analysts reckon that GM, which lost Dollars 4.5bn last year and recently
suffered a nine-day strike as it began seeking to pare its workforce,
clearly needs new marketing tools.
Using the GM card, consumers can earn a 5 per cent rebate, of up to Dollars
500 a year, accruable for seven years. This means that in seven years a GM
cardholder could obtain a rebate of up to Dollars 3,500 on the purchase or
lease of a GM vehicle.
In addition, GM cardholders will be able to receive a 10 per cent rebate by
using the card to buy goods or services from a group of GM corporate
partners, such as MCI, the telephone system, Avis, the car hire company, and
Marriott, the hotel chain.
GE also offers rebates for customers who use the GE card for Sprint
long-distance telephone calls or cable television services such as HBO and
Cinemax.
</TEXT>
