<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / P&amp;O increase fails to impress market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SLIGHTLY better than expected interim profits from Peninsular and Oriental
Steam Navigation Company failed to lift the company's shares, which fell 9p
to 340p after Lord Sterling, chairman, warned that second-half trading had
deteriorated in some areas and a continuing strong dollar would hit profits.
Pre-tax profits increased from Pounds 73.1m to Pounds 101.1m in the six
months to June 30, helped by a lower interest charge - from Pounds 71.7m to
Pounds 53.8m - following last year's Pounds 604m rights issue.
Lord Sterling said economic confidence appeared to have waned again. 'In
this climate . . . people are simply waiting,' he said.
Bovis Homes, the company's housebuilding arm, had a 'disappointing' first
half, although average selling prices were maintained. Sales levels in July
and August were again lower than in the same period last year.
Bovis Construction performed well, mainly due to overseas contracts, and the
company's order book is unchanged from six months ago at about Pounds 3.7bn.
P&amp;O European Ferries continued to perform well and carried record numbers of
passengers.
The ferry and cruise operations weathered recession because customers had
higher disposable incomes, Lord Sterling said, although cruise operations
were vulnerable to the weak dollar.
Operating profits for P&amp;O's divisions were: service industries down 12 per
cent to Pounds 46.2m, passenger shipping up 10 per cent to Pounds 48.1m,
container and bulk shipping up 17.2 per cent to Pounds 36.2m, investment
property up 19.4 per cent to Pounds 38.1m.
Housebuilding, construction and development saw increased losses from Pounds
3.5m to Pounds 13.7m. Most of the losses were incurred before P&amp;O and
Chelsfield restructured their joint venture property company, Pall Mall, in
April. The restructuring brought about Pounds 525m of debt on to P&amp;O's
balance sheet, and lifted net borrowings from Pounds 1.1bn to Pounds 1.6bn,
to take gearing on stockholders' funds of Pounds 2.3bn to 70 per cent.
Turnover and operating profits were barely changed at Pounds 2.46bn and
Pounds 154.9m, respectively. There was an extraordinary gain of Pounds
51.6m, mainly from the sale of part of the company's stake in a Hong Kong
container terminal.
Earnings increased 17.3 per cent to 12.2p while the dividend is maintained
at 13.5p.
