<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Biggest banks reject proposed watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S four largest clearing banks have told regulators they will not
participate in the Personal Investment Authority, the proposed
self-regulatory body.
The authority is intended to improve investor protection and spread the cost
of compensation.
The stance being taken by the banks could make it impossible to launch the
authority. Life insurance companies, which provide most funding for the
current self-regulatory structure, have said they will not participate
unless banks and building societies do.
If the PIA fails to get off the ground, the government is likely to review
the self-regulatory structure for the financial services industry, according
to banking sources. 'Sir Brian Hays (chairman of the PIA formation
committee) has been telling the banks that if PIA fails, self-regulation
fails,' said one banker familiar with the talks.
The authority is intended to merge Lautro, the self-regulatory body for the
life insurance and unit trust industries, and Fimbra, whose members are
independent financial intermediaries.
It is intended that unit trust sales forces who are members of Imro, which
oversees the fund management industry, would join the PIA as well. It would
need approval from 70 per cent of Lautro and Fimbra members.
The primary objection voiced by Barclays, National Westminster, Midland and
Lloyds is that they will be forced to increase substantially their
contributions to the Investors Compensation Scheme to cover defaults among
small independent financial intermediaries.
The banks also fear that life insurers, their keenest competitors, will
control at least a third of the votes on the PIA's board. Another fear is
that, if each member is entitled to a single vote on important issues, the
banks will be outvoted by small advisers on critical matters.
Under the Financial Services Act, companies must belong to one of four
self-regulatory organisations (SROs) covering different types of business,
but may not be forced to join any particular one.
They can also seek direct regulation from the Securities and Investments
Board which oversees the SROs. The life insurance and unit trust arms of the
clearing banks are mostly regulated by the SIB, as are some building
societies.
A consultative document outlining the charter of the PIA, designed to
regulate the sale and marketing of all retail financial products, is to be
released on September 24. The document is expected to offer inducements to
encourage all providers of retail financial services to join the planned
authority.
Background, Page 12
</TEXT>
