<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two notable series return at 8.30. The familiar and often excellent current
affairs programme This Week begins its last series on ITV. After 36 years it
will disappear at the end of this run, victim of ITV's Thatcherisation.
Today's programme investigates the growth of vigilante groups up and down
the country.
Waiting For God (8.30 BBC1) is among the best contemporary comedy series.
Graham Crowden and Stephanie Cole star as a couple of shrewd, bolshie
inmates of an old people's home. This, with its very high standard of acting
and direction, is what we shall extol in 20 years time as one of the marvels
of the good old days.
C4's documentary series about Nomads (9.00) began exceedingly well last week
with an extraordinary blend of anthropology and soap opera in Mauritania.
Today's subject is the Mongols and particularly the Xilinhot Nadam where
10,000 gather to watch archery, horse racing and wrestling. ITV screens the
last in the politically oh-so-correct American legal soap opera LA Law
(9.00) and BBC2 shows the first of nine 60-minute documentaries about how
the recession is affecting people, Present Imperfect (9.30).
