<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Directors' rises held down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION has held down top management's base pay rises this year,
according to figures published yesterday by Monks Partnership, the
independent remuneration advisers.
Rates of increase for the base salaries of main board directors fell from a
median of 14.3 per cent for the year to July 1991 to 7.7 per cent during the
present year to July, according to a survey based on data from more than 600
companies.
Senior managers of parent companies below board level saw their salary rises
decline from 9.3 per cent last year to 5.3 per cent this year.
The rates of pay increases of subsidiary company executives also fell,
although less dramatically.
Mr Tony Vernon-Harcourt, managing director of Monks, said: 'If we consider
what has been happening in recent months, top pay is no longer moving ahead
faster than the pay of the workforce as a whole. We would expect
differentials to narrow in times of recession.'
Most companies, he said, were expecting pay rises for senior executives of
about 5 per cent during the forthcoming year.
Pay rises for senior managers have evidently fallen more sharply than those
of the workforce generally, with government figures showing average earnings
increasing by about 7 per cent in a similar period, compared with 9.2 per
cent in the previous year.
Performance bonuses are a main component of senior managers' pay packages,
and those have also been restricted by the recession. During the past year,
the survey finds, 43 per cent of parent-company chief executives and 42 per
cent of the other main board directors who were eligible for a bonus did not
receive one because corporate performance fell short of minimum target
levels. That compares with 30 per cent and 33 per cent respectively for the
year to July 1991.
The proportion of eligible senior managers below board level in parent
companies who failed to receive bonuses rose from 37 per cent to 46 per
cent. Management Remuneration in the UK. Monks Partnership, Debden Green,
Saffron Walden, Essex CB11 3LX. Pounds 295.
</TEXT>
