<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Finance takes a hard look at self-regulation: Norma Cohen
sees obstacles to creating a new structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SELF-regulation, the battle cry of the financial services industry half a
decade ago, is now seen as dispensable by some who were once its staunchest
advocates.
The threat of US-style regulatory supervision once prompted competitors in
retail financial services to make compromises with each other. Now, those
competitors are suggesting that proposed reforms to self-regulation may be
so onerous and expensive that it is hard to imagine statutory regulation
being any worse.
Plans for a new super-body for retail financial services are coming under
attack from many of the businesses it was intended to cover.
The plan envisages merging Lautro, the self-regulatory body for the
insurance and unit trust industry, with Fimbra, the regulator for
independent financial advisers, and moving about one in three members of
Imro, the regulator for fund managers, into a new Personal Investment
Authority.
Imro members, though, have made clear that they are reluctant to join the
new body, and the life insurance companies have said they will not join
unless all their competitors join as well.
The life companies' main targets are the banks and building societies, most
of which have opted to have their retail financial services arms regulated
directly by the Securities and Investments Board.
Under the Financial Services Act, businesses may choose their regulator.
Such absence of compulsion has been the greatest obstacle to getting the new
authority off the ground.
Sources familiar with a consultative document to be released on September 24
say it contains a number of carrots and sticks designed to solicit as many
members as possible.
One stick will be a provision that marketing of unit trusts is specifically
an activity regulated by PIA - that is aimed at forcing many of Imro's
financial intermediary members into the new body. While Imro regulates their
affairs, it lacks the specific authority to make rules regarding the sale of
unit trusts.
The document proposes that the burden of contributions to the Investors
Compensation Scheme will be limited for those businesses which are not
independent financial advisers or which do not rely on such advisers to
distribute their products.
Members of the PIA's formation committee have suggested to the banks a
structure for funding the scheme which could limit their exposure to losses
from the large number of one-man-band Fimbra members who account for the
largest category of claims.
Claims of up to Pounds 50m a year will fall to independent advisers and
those who rely on them for product sales; other PIA members will only have
to pick up claims above that. The Pounds 50m ceiling is higher than that for
which that category of member is responsible now. Claims above a second
ceiling will be charged to all financial services groups. But banks say that
falls short of the sort of protection they want.
If plans to form the PIA are scrapped, it will leave un-answered the central
question that prompted its consideration in the first place: how to fund the
government's compensation scheme for small investors.
In 1991-92, large insurance companies paid Pounds 14m to the compensation
scheme on behalf of the small independent financial advisers that sell their
products but cannot afford to pay their levy. Insurance and unit trust
companies paid an additional Pounds 27m on their own behalf and have said
they are not prepared to continue to bail out their smaller members. Unless
new, richer groups can be made to pay more into the scheme, it cannot
continue, they say.
Banks and others say that in talks with the PIA's formation committee there
has been little to encourage them to join. For instance, Imro members sought
a rule to require the PIA to vet all members, even those transferring from
Fimbra and Lautro, hoping to drive out of the industry the businesses that
account for the largest number of claims on the compensation scheme. If such
vetting were made a condition, though, the PIA may not win the support of
the 70 per cent of Fimbra members which it needs to approve a merger.
Banks and building societies have been seeking a cap on the amount they can
be asked to pay into the scheme - a move likely to be anathema to the
insurance companies.
The banks also sought representation on the board of the PIA equal to the
one third expected to go to independent financial advisers. That would
require either that the board be expanded beyond its already unwieldy 24
members or that consumer representation be cut - both unpalatable to the
formation committee.
In the face of what may prove intractable disagreements, the
financial-services industry is increasingly coming to the view that
government regulation is unlikely to be worse than the system now in place.
'Most of our members believe the Financial Services Act hasn't worked at
all,' said one building society representative. A switch to statutory
regulation is not likely to be any worse, he said - a view increasingly
voiced by the life insurance industry as well.
The financial services industry is increasingly adopting the view that
failure of self-regulatory bodies to prevent the theft of more than Pounds
400m from pension funds controlled by the late Robert Maxwell has thrown the
entire system into doubt. In the words of Mr Christopher Sharples, chief
executive of the Securities and Futures Authority, self-regulation is
drinking in 'the last chance saloon'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
