FT  10 SEP 92 / Dispute over EETPU re-entry eases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEARS of a damaging inter-union split over the re-admission of the EETPU
electricians to the TUC appeared to be fading last night.
The National Union of Journalists was considering whether to go ahead with a
motion seeking to impose tough conditions on the reaffiliation talks.
However, its failure to agree with other unions about the wording of a
compromise means that few unions are likely to support its motion if it is
debated today.
The TUC's general council decided last night to oppose the motion if the NUJ
tables it.
The TUC's general council last night voted unanimously to ask the National
Union of Journalists to withdraw its motion.
If the journalists' union refuses, the general council will oppose the
motion.
TUC general secretary Norman Willis said: 'We have a very good general
council statement which shows the way forward and we do not need this
motion.'
Some unions, including Nalgo, which had previously planned to support the
NUJ, decided yesterday to vote against it.
The EETPU was expelled from the TUC in 1988. The negotiations on its
re-entry follow its merger with the AEU engineers earlier this year to form
the AEEU. TUC leaders hope they will be readmitted next year.
