<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Test for public services' resolve: The perceived threat of
the Citizen's Charter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN the prime minister launched his Citizen's Charter last year it seemed
to some public-sector unions that they had at last found a sympathetic ear
in government.
Since 1979 the public services had faced privatisation, pay restraints and
cuts in staffing. Union protests that such measures led to a deterioration
in the quality of services had cut no ice. Mr John Major's desire to raise
the quality of public services so that they stood comparison with the best
in the private sector seemed a welcome step forward.
Yesterday's TUC debate on the public services showed that any honeymoon
period with Mr Major has been brief. The unions have found much that is
attractive in setting service standards, giving more information to
customers and making services user-friendly. But Mr Major's agenda contains
much more than that. He wants to link pay much more closely to performance
in ways that would fragment national pay bargaining, and his programme to
expose the public services to competitive pressures threatens to undermine
union organisation, which has remained relatively intact in spite of the
ravages of Thatcherism.
Within days of the launch of the charter it became clear that it involved
much more than just name badges and complaints procedures. Mr Norman Lamont,
the chancellor, announced that he wanted to renegotiate Civil Service pay
agreements to increase performance pay and allow departments and agencies to
negotiate their own pay scales. Both measures, he said, would encourage
better service for the public.
For the unions, the desire to renegotiate pay agreements that had been
running for only three years came as an unpleasant shock. The objective of
increasing payment by results was hardly more acceptable. That is anathema
to union leaders, not least because it places more emphasis on individual
performance than on collective bargaining.
The plan to devolve pay responsibilities to the 30 departments and 70
executive agencies also posed a threat. Instead of half a dozen national
agreements covering most of the 550,000 civil servants, pay negotiations
would now fragment into more than 100 separate settlements, each needing
time and support from union head offices. As one general secretary put it:
'We will be very stretched by that.'
Much more subversive for the unions, however, was the government's white
paper on market testing, Competing for Quality, published last year. That
proposed putting a large segment of government services out to tender,
promising cost savings of up to 20 per cent that could be used to improve
service quality.
Ministers gave assurances that market testing would not inevitably lead to
contracting-out. Staff would be invited to put in bids for their own work.
However, the experience of local government, where compulsory competitive
tendering is well established, is that the process leads to a loss of
members and a weakening of union strength.
Nalgo, the public-sector white-collar union, has members working in
local-government sport and recreation departments that are now subject to
competitive tender. While the union remains opposed to tendering, it is
prepared to offer members advice on preparing a bid. That can, however, lead
branches to ask if they can make concessions on nationally agreed terms and
conditions to make their bid more competitive.
Ms Christina McAnea, a local government negotiator for Nalgo, said: 'We're
against that, naturally, but we have to be pragmatic if the branch wants to
go ahead. Guaranteed hours-of-work agreements and unsocial-hours payments
are most vulnerable.'
If the contract goes to an outside bidder, the chances are slight that the
new employer will recognise Nalgo - still less concede negotiating rights.
But the union tries to keep staff who transfer to the contractor in
membership, pointing out that it can still offer some protection and
services even if there are no negotiating rights. There is always the chance
that the contractor will lose the contract and the work will again be
internal.
Most of the Civil Service unions are adopting a three-pronged strategy
against market testing:
Campaigning against contracting-out particular jobs. The Inland Revenue
Staff Federation is making much of the threat to taxpayer confidentiality in
plans to contract out tax office typing.
Helping members to prepare winning bids if jobs are put out to tender. Two
Civil Service unions are talking to consultants about this. Recruiting staff
and securing negotiating rights if the work goes to outside contractors.
The last tactic will be easier for those unions whose members have already
faced the process of privatisation - such as IPMS, which represents
specialist civil servants.
Mr Bill Brett, IPMS general secretary, said: 'My membership - 100 per cent
Civil Service 20 years ago - is now one-third private sector. We have
members in GEC, Babcock &amp; Wilcox and British Aerospace and none of them has
ever left the union to join another.'
However bullish the unions are, contracting-out threatens to erode their
membership base at the same time as the fragmentation of pay negotiations
requires additional resources in time and staffing. The public services
remain almost 70 per cent unionised in spite of the unfavourable climate for
unions in the 1980s. They will do well to emerge from the 1990s with their
strength intact.
</TEXT>
