<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Accountants look to managers to survive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY half Britain's accountancy firms would like to employ a manager from
business to help them survive the recession, according to a survey published
yesterday.
Most are concerned about cashflow and property and staff costs. They also
expect profits to fall in the coming year.
The analysis of 587 small and medium-sized accountancy firms (with up to 20
partners) was conducted by Inform Corporation, a London information
technology consultancy.
In spite of their role as business advisers to companies, 45 per cent of the
firms said appointing an experienced business manager would make the biggest
single contribution to resolving their own trading and development
difficulties.
The admission contrasts strongly with the traditional hold that qualified
accountants have kept on management of their practices.
The survey showed that 52 per cent of firms expected partners' pay - and
thus profits - to fall in the coming year.
