FT  10 SEP 92 / Greater accountability for regulators urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TUC made its first serious contribution to the national debate on the
regulation of utilities yesterday by calling for greater accountability for
the regulators and less favouritism for business customers.
Moving a motion on the regulation of public-service industries, Mr Tony
Young, general secretary of the NCU communications union, said: 'For too
long we have ignored the role that regulators have to play. We've seen them
as agents of the Tory government, instead of realising that they could just
as easily work for the country as a whole.'
The call is a response to the government's sale of about 25 per cent of
British Telecom shares last year which ruled out the prospect of a return to
state control of the company under any future Labour government. Hitherto,
the possibility of renationalisation has prevented the NCU from entering the
regulation debate.
The motion urges new responsibilities for the regulators which would protect
the needs of all regions of the country, promote training and research and
ensure that both business and individual customers benefit from new
technology.
Mr Young criticised bodies such as Oftel, the telecommunications regulator,
for focusing on promoting maximum competition in public-service industries
and ignoring the national public interest.
He said that BT had reduced prices for business after privatisation, but
that average domestic bills had fallen very little.
The NCU also believes regulators should be made more accountable, through
more open decision-making and effective scrutiny by parliamentary select
committees.
