<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Treasury spells out preference for private sector: Unions
attack competitive tendering - Full employment campaign launched / Pressure
on utility watchdogs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CIVIL SERVICE departments tendering for government work may lose to the
private sector even when they can do the job as well and as cheaply, it
emerged yesterday.
Treasury advice to departments on competitive tendering says the
government's policy is to restrict the size of the public sector. 'In
general the presumption is that services should be provided by the private
sector, rather than the public sector,' the advice says.
'The fact that a public body can provide a service as quickly and as cheaply
as an outside contractor is not in itself a reason for extending
public-service activity,' it continues.
Contents of the memo were leaked by Civil Service unions yesterday as they
launched a campaign to publicise what they see as the harmful effects that
will result from competitive tendering.
Mr Bill Brett, general secretary of the IPMS Civil Service union, said 400
services in 28 departments were covered by market-testing arrangements
launched a year ago to pave the way for competitive tendering. Some 50,000
jobs in government departments were at risk, he said.
The unions believe their members may be forced to accept inferior conditions
in order for the departments to compete and they plan to warn the public
that they too will suffer.
Mr Brett said that if parts of the Health and Safety Executive were
contracted out, its ability to hold multi-disciplinary operations - for
example in the wake of disasters such as the King's Cross fire - would be
reduced.
Mr Clive Brooke, general secretary of the IRSF Civil Service union, said
contracting-out in the Inland Revenue would mean that companies' tax records
would be handled by other companies and possibly competitors.
The unions said market testing was proving expensive. In the Home Office, a
budget of Pounds 1.6m had been set aside and 40 people were working on
market testing.
Included in what the unions say is a comprehensive list of areas being
tested for marketing are large parts of the Ministry of Defence and the
armed forces and the private-letter section of the Foreign Office.
The TUC yesterday backed a resolution to campaign to 'ensure our members are
in the best position to fight the threats to all public-sector jobs'. The
resolution commits the TUC to make a campaign against privatisation and
contracting-out a 'top priority'.
</TEXT>
