<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / September bookings safe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TENS OF thousands of people who booked autumn holidays with Mowat, the
failed property and leisure group, will have to wait several days to find
out whether their money is safe, receivers Touche Ross said yesterday.
Touche Ross, which took control of Mowat yesterday morning after a syndicate
of 13 banks decided to put the company into administrative receivership,
said all bookings for holidays until October 3 would be honoured.
Mr Nigel Atkinson, one of the receivers, said he had not yet calculated how
many holidays had been booked for the period. Earlier this week, however, Mr
Brian Dunlop, Mowat chairman, put the number of bookings for the rest of
September at 20,000. He said there were an additional 43,000 bookings for
the remainder of the autumn season.
Mr Atkinson said two help-lines set up to provide information to Mowat
customers were busy throughout yesterday. Mowat owns 11 holiday parks in
England and offers cruise holidays on the Norfolk Broads. The helpline
numbers are: 0902 880800 (Holimarine) and 0692 670100 (Pennant Boats).
Mr Ian Birch, regional director of Lloyds Bank Commercial Service, which led
the syndicate, denied a claim by Mr Dunlop that the banks had acted too
quickly in calling in the receivers.
He said the banks had agreed to allow the company to continue operating if
it could raise Pounds 6.5m in new equity capital by August 27. That was
subsequently extended to last Monday, by which point Mowat had received firm
pledges for less than half that sum.
'If they had raised that Pounds 6.5m equity, I'm sure in my own mind that
the business would have continued,' Mr Birch said.
Mowat was not a member of the Association of British Travel Agents and its
holidays were not protected by a bond. The company's demise prompted further
calls yesterday for the government to protect holidaymakers.
Mr Mike Grindrod, Abta president, said he would be seeking a meeting with
Baroness Denton, consumer affairs minister, to discuss whether all travel
companies that take pre-payments should be licensed. Another unbonded
company, Land Travel, collapsed in July, leaving more than 40,000 people
with no prospect of recovering their money.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour consumer affairs spokesman, said the Department
of Trade and Industry should liaise with Abta on which travel companies
might be in trouble.
</TEXT>
