FT  10 SEP 92 / Crash blamed on property snags
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE director of the East Anglian tourist board, Mr Procter Naylor, said
yesterday that the collapse of Mowat was brought about by difficulties with
property concerns rather than with its three holiday centres in the region.
Mr Naylor expected that the sale to Broads Tours of Pennant Holidays,
Mowat's boat hire business, would still go ahead. Pennant Holidays' 175
cruisers and 38 day launches make up about 10 per cent of all hire boats on
the Norfolk Broads, where there are about 70 boat hire yards.
Mr Naylor, who said he was 'very sad' about Mowat's demise, said bookings
for its chalet and caravan sites had held up well in spite of the recession,
and receivers should have little difficulty in finding a suitable buyer.
Mr Len Funnell, chairman of Broads Tours, said he had held discussions with
Mowat's receivers yesterday and hoped the deal would still go through.
Boat hire bookings on the Norfolk Broads this summer were about 20 per cent
down on last year. Tourist operators estimated that Pennant Holidays'
bookings dropped even lower, in spite of a 30 per cent discount, partly
because it acted as its own boat holiday booking agent.
'I don't think it was the bad season that brought Mowat down,' Mr Funnell
said.
The Mowat group's Peerglow division had built homes primarily in
Staffordshire and Cheshire, with commercial and industrial developments
around the M25.
