<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Paisley walkout threatens talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE round-table talks on the political future of Northern Ireland hung in
the balance last night after a walkout by the Democratic Unionist leaders
the Rev Ian Paisley and Mr Peter Robinson.
The DUP leaders abandoned the 'strand two' talks at Stormont Castle, which
are being attended by the four constitutional parties in Northern Ireland
and the British and Irish governments.
They were complaining that two articles of the Irish Republic's
constitution, which establish a territorial claim to Northern Ireland and
which the Unionists wish to see dropped, should be a priority in the
negotiations.
After the walkout, Mr Paisley said: 'The Irish government has persuaded the
other people at the talks that articles two and three are not to be given
priority, and so they have put them at the bottom of the agenda. As long as
that prevails we will not be there.'
The DUP did, however, keep two junior representatives at the negotiating
table to monitor the discussions, and it is understood that Mr Paisley told
the other participants that he and Mr Robinson would return to the
negotiations once articles two and three are discussed.
In reaction to the walkout, Mr John Hume, the nationalist SDLP leader, said
that Mr Paisley seemed to want only to discuss his matters on the agenda and
no one else's.
He added: 'It doesn't seem to give any great commitment to try to have
genuine dialogue, which is about discussing other people's attitudes as well
as your own.
'What is being discussed are the obstacles which lie in the way of
north-south relations. Everybody has put forward a list of what obstacles
they see. I am quite prepared to discuss everybody's attitude but I would
not confine myself to my own.'
The DUP warned last night that it would respond to any statements made by
other participants to the talks, raising fears that the entire process begun
last April may be on the verge of breakdown amid a public exchange of mutual
recriminations.
The strand two talks are scheduled to continue up to September 28, with one
round at Stormont next week and the final round taking place in Dublin.
A 'strand three' meeting, between the British and Irish governments, is
scheduled for London this Friday.
</TEXT>
