<TEXT>
THE cross-party defence committee of MPs has taken the rare step of deciding
to meet during the parliamentary recess, to take evidence about the
deployment of British forces in the Gulf and in the former Yugoslavia,
Alison Smith writes.
Just a week after Mr John Major dismissed a request from the Labour
leadership to recall the Commons to discuss such issues, along with the
economy, the Tory-dominated committee announced that it planned to question
Mr Archie Hamilton, the armed forces minister, later this month.
Meeting in the recess is not unprecedented for a Commons committee, but it
is an unusual move which reflects the concern among MPs over the deployment
of British troops.
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, the Tory chairman of the committee, denied that its
decision was a criticism of the prime minister's refusal to bring MPs back
to Westminster to debate foreign affairs. It was important for the committee
to keep on top of the issue.
Six British Tornado aircraft began taking part in the United Nations
enforcement of the 'no fly' exclusion area in southern Iraq late last month.
Some 1,800 British troops are ready to leave for Bosnia when the UN gives
the signal.
