FT  10 SEP 92 / Labour confusion on ERM deepens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DISARRAY within the Labour party over UK membership of the European exchange
rate mechanism deepened yesterday as Mr David Blunkett, shadow health
secretary, called for the opposition to support a currency realignment.
Mr Blunkett's words came the day after Mr Bryan Gould, shadow heritage
secretary, launched a sharp attack on the Maastricht treaty and on the
deflationary nature of the ERM.
Speaking in Sheffield, Mr Blunkett welcomed the measures the party had
already outlined, but added: 'The benefits which were gained 25 years ago
when belatedly sterling was realigned, could provide the basis for our
economic recovery today.'
Although Mr Blunkett's words are more cautious than the statement from Mr
Gould, they intensify pressure on the party leadership to ensure that there
is a full and open debate on the stance it should take over the impact on
the domestic economy of the high interest rates needed to support the pound
in the ERM.
'If interest rates are not to rise with further damage to industry and
millions of families with mortgages, then realignment within the ERM would
appear to be a necessity,' Mr Blunkett said last night.
He argued that a comprehensive realignment was vital for the survival of
manufacturing, but did not say whether he thought the UK should act
unilaterally if there were not enough support for a general realignment.
Mr Gould yesterday refused to rule out resigning from the shadow cabinet
over Europe.
'That is, I suppose, in theory always open to any member of the shadow
cabinet on any issue,' he said on BBC breakfast news when asked about
Maastricht.
He added, however: 'I have no reason to suppose that when the shadow cabinet
reaches a decision it won't be one I cannot support.'
He went on to make clear that he 'did not think for a moment' that there was
a damaging split in Labour's leadership.
</TEXT>
