<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / UN to step up protection for peacekeepers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER, ROBERT MAUTHNER and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations last night signalled a tougher line to safeguard the
lives of peacekeeping troops in Bosnia-Hercegovina, amid growing outrage at
the killing of two French officers in a relief convoy ambush at Sarajevo on
Tuesday.
Responding to calls for troops to return fire if attacked, the Security
Council said there was urgent need for 'reinforcing the security and
protection' of UN personnel in Bosnia. Members nations were ready 'to adopt
without delay measures to this end.'
The Council condemned the relief convoy attack, which the UN peacekeeping
force blamed squarely on the largely Moslem forces of the Bosnian
government. The UN force also accused Moslem fighters of carrying out three
other recent attacks on peacekeepers.
Reflecting growing frustration and anger in the UN force, its commander
called on Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic to dispense 'immediate and
salutary justice' to those responsible for the killing of the French
officers.
The UN also confirmed that an Italian relief plane that crashed near
Sarajevo last week was shot down. The aircraft, whose crew of four died, was
flying over an area controlled by Croats, but the UN did not say who was to
blame.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, Britain's defence secretary, said UK troops about to go
to Bosnia-Hercegovina should be allowed to return fire.
He condemned as 'repulsive' Tuesday's machine gun and mortar attack on the
UN relief convoy near Sarajevo airport. Although two French peacekeepers
were killed and three wounded, the UN troops did not fire back at the forces
ambushing it.
Mr Rifkind said, however, it was a 'crucial requirement' for any soldier to
be able to defend himself.
Mr Rifkind's remarks reflect growing calls from the countries contributing
to the 16,000-strong Yugoslav peacekeeping force for their lightly armed
troops to use force if attacked.
The French government earlier yesterday implicitly accused Bosnian Moslem
forces of being responsible for the death of the soldiers.
Until now, the UN and members of the peacekeeping force have been reluctant
to single out Serbs, Moslems or Croats for blame in Bosnia.
Condemning the attack, Mr Roland Dumas, the French foreign minister, said it
underlined the urgent need to find an answer to the UN peacekeepers'
security problems.
Philip Stephens adds: The UK cabinet is today expected to give the formal
go-ahead for despatch of up to 1,800 British troops to Bosnia. Whitehall
officials said the troops, on stand-by in Germany, could be sent as early as
next week.
Commons defence group recalled, Page 8
</TEXT>
