<PROFILE>_AN-CIJB4AAIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920910
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Italian PM seeks emergency powers over economy: Amato may
rule by decree during a crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ITALY's embattled government is to seek emergency powers from parliament
which would allow it to rule by decree in the event of economic emergency.
The two-month-old coalition led by Professor Giuliano Amato, the prime
minister, also announced a series of economic measures yesterday as it tries
desperately to establish credibility in the face of a foreign exchange
crisis.
Prof Amato said the special powers would include the right to halt approved
government spending or borrowing plans without parliamentary approval, to
alter taxes and to speed investment in areas of the economy where it was
considered necessary.
After a long cabinet meeting, the government announced it would sell off
shares in Credito Italiano, one of the country's top five commercial banks,
and Nuovo Pignone, the heavy engineering company controlled by ENI, the
state oil concern.
The cabinet also approved a series of measures to tighten budgetary control
and tax evasion, plus the abolition of tax exemption on Italian purchase of
bonds issued by multilateral financial institutions such as the World Bank
and European Investment Bank. For all future purchases, a 12.5 per cent tax
will apply.
With the Italian currency under persistent pressure for weeks on the foreign
exchange markets, Prof Amato in a press conference last night stressed his
government's commitment to defend the lira within the European Monetary
System and reduce the country's huge budget deficit. Industrialists and
bankers had pressed the government - following last week's 1.75 point rise
in the discount rate to 15 per cent - to generate confidence by announcing a
privatisation.
The cabinet meeting was brought forward by two days in an attempt by the
four-party coalition government to demonstrate to nervous financial markets
evidence of a will to act.
The government's intention to avail itself of special powers for quick
action in the event of an economic crisis could have potentially
far-reaching consequences. The proposal marks a recognition that Italy's
existing parliamentary procedures are too slow for the necessary rapid
decision-making at a time of financial turbulence. The law would permit the
government to act by decree to, for instance, raise revenues once a
'neutral' party - defined as the governor of the Bank of Italy - accepted
there was an economic crisis.
Before the measures were announced, the lira slipped slightly against the
D-Mark to close at L764.55 compared with L764.14.
The Milan bourse rose nearly 2 per cent, while shares in Credito Italiano,
buoyed by press leaks ahead of the announcement, jumped nearly 14 per cent,
forcing trading in its stock to be suspended.
'The markets have been baying for blood, and maybe the government has given
them a little of what they wanted,' said one banker. The decision on the
privatisations was taken rapidly and the details of the sell-offs will take
time to emerge.
Credito Italiano is 67 per cent controlled by IRI, the state holding company
which last month became a joint stock company. The bank, with total assets
of L94,347bn at the end of 1991, has seen its shares rise 23 per cent in the
last three days in what had been an otherwise depressed bourse. The bank
earned net profits last year of L297bn.
But investors were taken by surprise by the inclusion of Nuovo Pignone in
the government's sell-off plans. The company last year turned in profits of
L32bn on turnover of L1367bn.
Italy embarks on road to electoral reform Page 2
Italy bows to bankers over Efim debt Page 19
