<HEADLINE>
FT  10 SEP 92 / Major calls for overhaul of G7 summits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR has called for a radical overhaul of the Group of Seven's
annual summits to re-establish their role in shaping effective leadership
among the rich industrial nations.
In a confidential letter to the leaders of the US, Japan, Germany, Italy,
France and Canada, the prime minister has proposed they shed the vast
bureaucracy that has built up around their annual gatherings.
Instead, he has suggested that the summits return to the original 'fireside
chat' formula devised by Mr Valery Giscard D'Estaing and Mr Helmut Schmidt
when the then French and German leaders called the first in 1975.
One idea is that the G7 should abandon the long pre-drafted communiques
covering all aspects of world economic and political developments in favour
of a concise statement of priorities.
A more radical proposal floated in Whitehall is that the foreign and finance
ministers, who often dominate the working sessions at the summits, should be
banished.
Ministers in the UK and elsewhere have recognised that recent summits have
failed to get to grips with the failing world economy and the turmoil in the
former communist bloc.
Both Mr Major and Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, believe that the
summits - which also bring together hundreds of officials from the seven
countries - have become too stage-managed.
The detailed preparations have reduced the talks among heads of state to
carefully rehearsed statements of previous positions.
Mr Major has been particularly frustrated by the failure of two consecutive
summits - London in 1991 and Munich in 1992 - to achieve a breakthrough in
the stalled Uruguay round of trade talks in the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade (GATT).
He believes that uncertainty over the future of the world trading system has
contributed greatly to the slowdown in economic growth.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
