<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / International Company News: NY Times Dollars 35m item to
reflect closure cost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE New York Times will record an after-tax charge of about Dollars 35m, or
45 cents a share, in its third quarter results, reflecting the cost of
shutting down The Gwinnett Daily News, a daily newspaper operating in the
suburbs of Atlanta, Georgia.
Cox Enterprises, the regional media group, has agreed to buy some of the
paper's fixed assets.
The New York Times bought the Gwinnett newspaper in 1987 for an estimated
Dollars 88m. The paper had a circulation of 50,000 and was popular with its
readership, but annual losses have continued at about Dollars 4m.
Mr Bill Adler, a spokesman for the New York Times group, said the newspaper
was a victim of recession and stiff advertising competition among Atlanta
dailies: 'The key is that things were not getting any better. The situation
was getting worse,' he said.
Mr Adler said the New York Times hired a broker last summer to try to sell
the paper, but none of the 40 prospective buyers was interested.
Although cash flow will be increased by the money to be paid to the Times by
Cox for offices, equipment, subscription lists and a new printing press, the
New York Times is still likely to suffer a net loss. Analysts had been
expecting a third quarter net profit of about Dollars 8m before the news of
the special Gwinnett charge.
For the first six months of 1992, the New York Times group's net income was
Dollars 29.2m, against Dollars 10.5m in the first half of last year.
Revenues were Dollars 888.5m, compared with Dollars 857.3m in the first half
of 1991.
