<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / Bush taken to task over Nafta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR Democratic senators have taken President George Bush to task for
endangering the North American free trade agreement's chances of passing
through Congress by seeking to use it as a campaign issue.
Senator Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, a staunch supporter of the Nafta
negotiations between the US, Canada and Mexico, complained yesterday that Mr
Bush was 'deliberately politicising' the agreement.
Mr Bush and other Republicans have accused Governor Bill Clinton, the
Democratic presidential candidate, of equivocation by saying he is in favour
of free trade but refusing an outright endorsement of Nafta.
'Politicising this agreement will not help its prospects in Congress,' Mr
Bentsen warned, adding that Mr Clinton could not be expected to decide on
the 2,000-page agreement when its full text had only just been made
available.
Senator Max Baucus of Montana went a step further and accused the
administration of rushing Nafta through in time for last month's Republican
convention in Houston - giving short shrift to concerns over environmental
protection and job displacement.
Mexico's trade deficit deteriorated sharply in the first half of this year
to Dollars 9.4bn (Pounds 4.72bn), more than double that in the same period
last year, according to the Finance Ministry, writes Damian Fraser in Mexico
City.
</TEXT>
