<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / Wimpey warns on homes market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECESSION in the construction industry could continue for another two
years and would leave very few survivors unless the government took steps to
help the industry, the chairman of Britain's second largest housebuilder
warned yesterday.
Sir Clifford Chetwood, chairman of Wimpey, was commenting after the company
announced a Pounds 7.2m first-half loss and reduced its interim dividend by
half.
He said the recession in housebuilding had run for three years and could
stretch for a further two.
'If we face a five-year recession with no assistance by government, there
will be very few construction firms left,' Sir Clifford said.
He appealed to the government to introduce measures to stimulate the housing
market which, he said, would encourage greater confidence in the economy as
a whole.
'Every day that their house is seen as a wasting, dwindling asset - a false,
unwise investment - the longer we put off a return to consumer confidence,'
Sir Clifford said.
'This does not just affect the housing industry. it hits motor cars, white
goods, furniture, manufacturing right across the board.
'People will not spend when their safety-net, when the money that is
invested in their property, has been seen to vanish from under them and
threatens to diminish even further.'
Sir Clifford, a former president of the Building Employers Confederation,
criticised government economic policies which concentrated solely on
defeating inflation. He said: 'The defeat of inflation is a laudable goal,
but on its own will do nothing to rekindle confidence among those whose nest
egg has disappeared and who will have to spend the rest of their lives
paying off the liability which their investment has become.'
He continued: 'There can be schemes devised which are neither short-term nor
impulsive. It should not be beyond our wit as a nation to identify them and
implement them to help the country as a whole in the most effective way at
our disposal - by getting the housing market back to steady growth.'
He said he did not want to say what measures he would like the government to
introduce to assist home buyers. Previously he has advocated removal of
stamp duty from house purchase and increased mortgage tax relief.
Lex, Page 20 Wimpey results, Page 21
</TEXT>
