<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / Red-blooded leaders change battle cry to 'Pensions':
Behind-the-scenes manoeuvrings by the big unions in the wake of the Maxwell
affair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TO RED-BLOODED union leaders the issue of pensions has been best left to the
backroom boffins at HQ - worthy, but hardly the stuff of which stirring
speeches are made.
The scandal over the Maxwell pension funds has changed all that,
highlighting the potential threat to employees and pensioners from lack of
controls on the operation of occupational pension funds. The pensions
ombudsman recently expressed his frustration about the narrow limits of his
watchdog role and said he had been overwhelmed by the volume of complaints.
The union movement, marginalised for so long, clearly has a legitimate
interest as the only national grouping to represent those employees and
pensioners.
Mr Bryn Davies, actuary with Union Pension Services, says: 'The debate at
last year's TUC didn't excite a lot of interest. But this year everyone I
talk to in unions sees pensions as perhaps the key issue for unions in the
1990s.'
The debates scheduled today at the TUC conference will conclude by restating
the movement's wish for a number of legal reforms. But for all this, it is
not the TUC itself which will make the running on the issue. Pensions do not
even figure on the list of six areas identified by the TUC earlier this year
as priorities for action.
An unofficial grouping of the larger unions, initiated by the GMB general
union and including the TGWU general union and the MSF general technical
union, has been meeting for some weeks behind the scenes to discuss pensions
strategy.
This could be seen as further evidence of the increasing irrelevance of the
TUC - if pensions are one of the most important issues for unions in the
1990s, it is significant that the leaders of the big unions feel happiest
getting on with the job on their own.
The group's target is the independent commission, under Professor Roy Goode,
set up by the government to review the framework of pension legislation over
the next year. The group hopes to raise the profile of unions in the pension
debate and put forward a number of well-constructed submissions to the
commission.
A TUC fringe meeting today will launch a 'charter for pension-fund
democracy' and a special conference on the issue is likely to follow at the
end of the year.
The campaign will focus on representation on boards of trustees. From
arguing that there should be an equal division of power between employees
and companies, unions have moved to demanding that employees should have
majority representation. The argument is that pensions are pay, so fund
members should have the right to control fund assets.
The charter will also demand the legal separation of company and
pension-fund activities and assets, the right for pensioners to be
represented on trustee boards, the right to full and up-to-date information
for scheme members, paid time off for employee representatives to receive
training and carry out their duties, and trustee powers to appoint outside
advisers.
Apparent contradictions in unions' arguments over control and use of
surpluses remain unresolved. Employers say that if they bear the risk of
having to top up funds to pay benefits, they should control those schemes
and benefit from pensions holidays when times are good.
Employers say unions want to have their cake and eat it - that they are
asking for both democratic control and financial guarantees. Mr Davies says
existing guarantees are, in law, virtually worthless. 'Employers rarely have
an inescapable commitment to pay the expected benefits, come what may,' he
says.
The next stage of the debate within unions on pensions may need to move to a
more sophisticated level with the offer - currently impossible for some
unionists even to contemplate - of a trade-off between some of that phantom
security and increased democracy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-4032</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIIBPACTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920909
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / Security training call for Tube
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON Underground staff should be trained at inspecting suspect packages to
curb the number of delays caused by false alarms, according to a report
published yesterday.
The study suggests that passengers should be made more aware of the need to
keep belongings with them.
The report was commissioned after an incident in Bethnal Green, east London,
18 months ago in which six Central Line Underground trains were stuck in
tunnels when two suspect briefcases were discovered.
It was five hours before all 6,000 passengers were evacuated.
That incident came at a time of soaring security alerts on London
Underground and British Rail. Between 1990 and last year anonymous calls
rose from 446 to 1,683, suspect packages from 270 to 1,961 and devices found
from five to eight.
Mr Brian Appleton, the report's author, paints a generally favourable
picture of the work being done by British Rail, British Transport Police and
London Underground to reduce the disruption caused by security alerts.
He rejects suggestions that the balance of risk involved in bomb threats
should be recognised by continuing to run train services in the face of the
threats.
The report says that the degree of risk can shift wildly from month to month
depending on the political environment.
The report suggests that the risk to Underground passengers from fires has
shrunk to the point where London Underground and the London Fire Brigade
should be working to reduce the disruption caused by their reaction to fire
reports.
Appleton Inquiry Report, HMSO, Pounds 4.25.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
