<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / Pressure on Labour over Maastricht: Calls for devaluation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR policy on Europe came under double pressure yesterday when several
union leaders at the TUC congress in Blackpool called for devaluation of the
pound and Mr Bryan Gould, shadow heritage secretary, described the
Maastricht treaty as 'not the right blueprint for Europe'.
The call for devaluation was led by Mr John Edmonds, leader of the GMB
general union, one of the largest Labour-affiliated unions. He said: 'The
pound is over-valued. An early realignment is essential if we are to live
without further agony in the ERM.'
Mr Edmonds, who was supported by several other large unions including the
general union TGWU, the public service union Nalgo and white collar union
MSF, added: 'Most people in industry know that the pound is over-valued.
Realignment is now inevitable.'
He said he believed that Britain should remain in the European exchange rate
mechanism. Earlier yesterday he strongly endorsed the TUC's support for the
Maastricht treaty without a referendum, a position backed by a large
majority of congress delegates.
But Mr Edmonds argued that high interest rates were strangling the economy.
'The best way to deal with the problem is through a revaluation of the
D-Mark but both the French and British governments are against that,' he
said.
The union call for devaluation will ensure a rough ride on the issue for the
Labour leadership at the party conference in three weeks. Labour has been
reluctant to call for any tampering with the pound's position in the
European exchange rate mechanism.
Mr John Smith, Labour leader, in Blackpool for dinner with the TUC general
council last night, said he was 'not in favour of a devaluation of sterling
because that would not assist in reducing interest rates'. But he added that
the EC 'should not rule out a revaluation of the D-Mark'.
Disarray over Europe on the Labour front bench intensified with Mr Gould's
call to use the failure of the Maastricht agreement to set out a new agenda
for Europe.
Mr Gould said: 'Britain should now take the lead in acknowledging that the
Maastricht treaty is deeply flawed and has failed as a consequence to secure
the endorsement of the people of Europe. This is as much an opportunity as a
problem.'
While the Labour leadership says the party will not decide what line to take
until the bill to ratify Maastricht returns to the House of Commons, Mr
Gould's remarks strike a very different tone from the conditional support
for the treaty expressed by Mr Smith and Mr John Cunningham, shadow foreign
secretary.
Mr Gould, who challenged Mr Smith for the Labour leadership in the summer,
launched a particular attack on the European exchange rate mechanism.
He said: 'A European economy wrecked by recession simply cannot afford to
hand economic policy over to unelected bankers who will enforce treaty
provisions requiring massive cuts in pubic spending and giving an overriding
priority to price stability at the expense of jobs and living standards.'
In Blackpool yesterday Mr Smith indicated that he did not propose to
discipline Mr Gould for his statement. 'I think he was speculating, as I
think we are all entitled to do, on the effect of the Danish negative
response to their referendum,' he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
