<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / Dumping of arms at sea comes under fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MINISTRY of Defence has not notified international regulators that it
has dumped bombs, shells and hand grenades at a site in the Atlantic, it
emerged yesterday, prompting allegations that the government was in breach
of international conventions.
The disclosure comes as concern is growing about the environmental costs of
decommissioning military equipment as defence forces are reduced.
The London Dumping Convention, to which the UK is a signatory, allows
military dumping under 'sovereign immunity' clauses. But Greenpeace, the
environmental group, said in a report yesterday that the MoD had an
obligation to notify the LDC's secretariat of military dumping.
Mr Chris Smith, Labour's environment spokesman, said yesterday the
government had 'a clear duty of information'.
The amount of ammunition dumped at the Atlantic site, 400 miles west of
Land's End, will be 8,405 tonnes this year. It was 1,093 tonnes last year.
From the end of this year, when the Oslo Convention on sea dumping comes
into force, the MOD will bury old ammunition in pits.
</TEXT>
