<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / Lamont fends off criticism with strong rejection of
devaluation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT has moved to pre-empt a row over the economy at next
month's Conservative party conference with a robust defence of his refusal
to devalue the pound.
The chancellor reassured Tory activists that the economy would emerge from
recession during 'the course of this year'.
His comments, in the latest issue of the party newspaper, will be followed
tomorrow by a renewed attempt from Mr John Major to reassure industrialists
and to steady the nerves of government supporters over economic prospects.
The prime minister, who earlier this week sought to quell the revolt within
his party over the Maastricht treaty, plans to restate his conviction that
the pain of recession will bring the reward of a sustained upturn.
Conservative MPs returning from their summer break have reported growing
unrest in constituency associations over the length and depth of the
recession. Ministers are adding their voice to predictions that criticism of
Mr Lamont's strategy may sour planned conference celebrations of April's
election victory.
A number of constituencies - whose associations tend to be dominated by
small business owners and the self-employed - have tabled critical motions.
Most call for early interest rate reductions, with some making a link with
the need to devalue or withdraw sterling from the European exchange rate
mechanism.
In the long and strongly worded article published in Conservative Newsline,
Mr Lamont rejected suggestions that a lower pound would speed economic
upturn. He insisted: 'Devaluation would not help recovery. It would lead to
a collapse in market confidence and a damaging rise in interest rates.' He
added that withdrawal from the ERM would be a bigger mistake. 'We would see
a huge fall in the pound and an explosion in inflation.'
Anticipating what is expected to be a central theme of Mr Major's speech in
Edinburgh, Mr Lamont promised that the current strategy would bring an end
to 'stop-go' economics.
The sharp and continuing fall in Britain's inflation rate had been
overlooked. 'Yet those figures tell us more about the future of the British
economy and our long-term prospects than any other bit of economic news.'
But those who argued for what would be a 'quite disastrous' decision by the
government to ease up in the battle against inflation had to recognise that
prices were rising faster in the UK than in France or Germany.
He pointed to a range of economic indicators to dismiss predictions that the
recession might be prolonged indefinitely. Manufacturing output had risen
for two successive quarters, exports and retail sales had increased in the
second quarter and the growth of unemployment had slowed.
The chancellor added: 'I expect growth to resume in the course of this
year.' The recovery would be slow at first but the 'critical point' was that
'the only way to secure a long-lasting recovery is to put in place a stable
medium-term framework which will deliver low inflation'.
