<HEADLINE>
FT  09 SEP 92 / School standards plan attracts over 4,000 would-be
inspectors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 4,000 people have applied to become school inspectors under the
government's new scheme for monitoring standards in England's schools.
Launching the Office for Standards in Education (Ofsted) yesterday,
Professor Stewart Sutherland, chief inspector of schools, said the selection
of the first 210 inspectors would start next week, with teams ready to start
work in September 1993.
From next year, all schools in England will be subject to inspection at
least once every four years by a team appointed by Ofsted, the successor to
Her Majesty's Inspectorate, under the direction of the chief inspector.
Inspection teams, which must include at least one lay member without direct
teaching experience, will be licensed by Ofsted. Licensed teams will bid for
inspections, most likely school-by-school, with Ofsted awarding inspections
on the basis of price and quality. Of the 4,000 applicants, 1,500 are from
individuals applying to be inspection team leaders, the majority wishing to
inspect secondary schools.
In line with government hopes, lay inspector posts are proving attractive to
individuals from private sector backgrounds. Of 100 applications processed,
24 are from present or past consultants, 21 from managers, six from company
directors and six from 'professionals'.
Prof Sutherland said: 'My office is now heavily engaged in the assessment of
this avalanche of applications. Nearly 1,000 have already passed the first
scrutiny and will be invited to take a place on the Ofsted training scheme.'
Schools thought to be 'at risk' of failing to offer a satisfactory education
will be given priority for inspection by Ofsted. Where a school is found to
be 'at risk', its governors will be expected to take urgent action to
improve standards.
Mr John Patten, education secretary, intends to take powers to send in a
national taskforce to run schools which fail to improve themselves after
being designated 'at risk'.
Ms Ann Taylor, Labour's education spokesman, said the new system was 'a
recipe for uneven and sub-standard inspection', adding: 'Inspectors will be
sent to schools with little training.'
Observer Page 19
